\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 2.       Chamaecyparis}           Spach
\par       

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By †T.G. Tutin.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Like {\i Cupressus} but with flattened twigs; female cones ripening in the first year or rarely early in the second, globose; seeds up to 5 on each scale. Seedlings and occasional branches of older plants of all species produce acicular, patent leaves.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. C. lawsoniana} (A. Murray) Parl.,{\i  Ann. Mus. Firenze} nov. ser., {\b 1:} 181 (1866) ({\i Cupressus lawsoniana} A. Murray). Tree up to 65 m. Leaves opposite and decussate, the lateral ones larger than the others, all closely appressed, acute, with translucent glands, and with white markings beneath. Male cone pink or red; female cone c. 8 mm in diameter, globose, yellowish-brown when ripe; scales 8, each with a central depression in which is a projecting ridge. Seeds 2-4(5) on each scale, ovoid, with conspicuous resinous tubercles, winged.{\i  Widely planted for timber and shelter, and locally naturalized}. [Au Br Da Ga Ge Hb It Lu No Rm Tu.] ({\i W. United States}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Other commonly cultivated species are{\b  C. obtusa} (Siebold & Zucc.) Siebold & Zucc. in Endl.,{\i  Syn. Conif.} 63 (1847), from Japan, with obtuse, minutely glandular leaves with white X- or Y-shaped markings beneath;{\b  C. pisifera} (Siebold & Zucc.) Siebold & Zucc. in Endl.,{\i  op. cit.} 64 (1847), from Japan, with acute, obscurely glandular leaves with white markings beneath, and cone 5-6 mm in diameter; and{\b  C. nootkatensis} (D. Don) Spach,{\i  Hist. Vég.} ({\i Phan}.){\b  2:} 333 (1834), from W. North America, with dull green, eglandular leaves without white markings, and with cones which ripen early in the second year.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 3.            Thuja}                 L.
\par      

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By †T.G. Tutin.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Like{\i  Cupressus} but twigs flattened; female cones oblong or conical, ripening in the first year; scales thin and flexible; seeds up to 5 on each scale.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. T. plicata} D. Don in Lamb.,{\i  Descr. Gen. Pinus}{\b  2:} 19 (1824). Tree up to 65 m. Trunk not branched from the base. Leaves opposite and decussate, ovate, acute or obtuse, appressed, eglandular or with an obscure gland, usually with faint white markings beneath. Female cone c. 12 mm, conical, brown when ripe; scales 10-12, thin, with a thickened process on the inner side, projecting beyond the thin, triangular, deflexed apex. Seeds 2 or 3 per scale, elliptical, winged.{\i  Planted for timber, and locally naturalized}. [Au Br Da Ge It Lu No.] ({\i W. North America}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 {\b T. occidentalis} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 1002 (1753), from E. North America, is also sometimes planted, mainly in C. Europe. It has conspicuously glandular leaves which are yellowish- or bluish-green and without white markings beneath; the female cones are oblong and bright brown when ripe.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 {\b T. orientalis} L.,{\i  loc. cit.} (1753), from China, is occasionally planted, mainly for ornament. It usually has several basal branches as long as the main stem, entirely green leaves, the female cone with 6(-8) thick scales, each with a stout hooked or recurved apical boss, and seeds without a wing. It has a chromosome number of 2n = 22.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 4.          Tetraclinis}            Masters
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By †T.G. Tutin.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Monoecious tree. Buds concealed by the leaves. Twigs flattened. Leaves in groups of 4, the lateral ones larger than the others, all adnate to the twig except at the scale-like apex. Female cones solitary; scales 4, in a single whorl, valvate, woody. Seeds with 2 wide wings.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 The only species.
\par

