\pard\f0\fs28 Monoecious or dioecious trees or shrubs. Leaves opposite or in whorls of 3, acicular or scale-like, always acicular in young plants; frequently all scale-like in mature plants, or all acicular, or a combination of both. Female cones axillary or terminal, ripening in the first, second or third year, usually ovoid to globose, indehiscent, berry-like; cone-scales fleshy, coalescent. Seeds ovoid or oblong, angled or terete, 1-12 in each cone, never winged.
